name: dart:io

children.name: exitCode=
children.comment:
Global exit code for the Dart VM.

The exit code is global for the Dart VM and the last assignment to
exitCode from any isolate determines the exit code of the Dart VM
on normal termination.

children.name: exit
children.comment:
Exit the Dart VM process immediately with the given [status] code.

This does not wait for any asynchronous operations to terminate. Using
[exit] is therefore very likely to lose data.

children.name: _WebSocketProtocolProcessor
update
children.comment: Process data received from the underlying communication channel.

children.name: closed
children.comment: Indicate that the underlying communication channel has been closed.

The web socket protocol processor handles the protocol byte stream
which is supplied through the [:update:] and [:closed:]
methods. As the protocol is processed the following callbacks are
called:

  [:onMessageStart:]
  [:onMessageData:]
  [:onMessageEnd:]
  [:onClosed:]
  [:onError:]

children.name: WebSocket
onopen=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when a web socket connection has
been established.

children.name: onerror=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when the web socket connection
encountered an error.

children.name: onclose=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when the web socket connection is
closed.

children.name: close
children.comment: Closes the web socket connection.

children.name: onmessage=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when a message has been
received.

children.name: send
children.comment:
Sends data on the web socket connection. The data in [data] must
be either a [:String:], or a [:List<int>:] holding bytes.

children.name: readyState
children.comment: Returns the current state of the connection.

children.name: bufferedAmount
children.comment: Returns the number of bytes currently buffered for transmission.

children.name: extensions
children.comment:
The extensions property is initially the empty string. After the
web socket connection is established this string reflects the
extensions used by the server.

children.name: protocol
children.comment:
The protocol property is initially the empty string. After the
web socket connection is established the value is the subprotocol
selected by the server. If no subprotocol is negotiated the
value will remain [:null:].

children.name: WebSocket
children.comment:
Create a new web socket connection. The URL supplied in [url]
must use the scheme [:ws:]. The [protocols] argument is either a
[:String:] or [:List<String>:] specifying the subprotocols the
client is willing to speak.

Alternative web socket client interface. This interface is compliant
with the W3C browser API for web sockets specified in
http://dev.w3.org/html5/websockets/.

children.name: CloseEvent
wasClean
children.comment: Returns whether the connection was closed cleanly or not.

children.name: code
children.comment:
Returns the web socket connection close code provided by the
server.

children.name: reason
children.comment:
Returns the web socket connection close reason provided by the
server.
Event delivered when a web socket connection is closed.

children.name: MessageEvent
data
children.comment:
The type of [message] is either [:String:] or [:List<int>:]
depending on whether it is a text or binary message. If the
message is empty [message] will be [:null:]
If the message is a [:List<int>:] then it will contain byte values
from 0 to 255.
Event delivered when there is data on a web socket connection.

children.name: Event
children.comment:
Base class for the events generated by the W3C complient browser
API for web sockets.

children.name: WebSocketClientConnection
onRequest=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when the request object for the
opening handshake request is ready. This callback can be used if
one needs to add additional headers to the opening handshake
request.

children.name: onOpen=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when a web socket connection has
been established.

children.name: onMessage=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when a message has been
received. The type of [message] is either [:String:] or
[:List<int>:], depending on whether it is a text or binary
message. If the message is empty [message] will be [:null:].
If the message is a [:List<int>:] then it will contain byte values
from 0 to 255.

children.name: onClosed=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when the web socket connection is
closed. [status] indicates the reason for closing. For network
errors the value of [status] will be
WebSocketStatus.ABNORMAL_CLOSURE].

children.name: onNoUpgrade=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when the response object for the
opening handshake did not cause a web socket connection
upgrade. This will be called in case the response status code is
not 101 (Switching Protocols). If this callback is not set and the
server does not upgrade the connection, the [:onError:] callback will
be called.

children.name: send
children.comment:
Sends a message. The [message] must be a [:String:] or a
[:List<int>:] containing bytes. To send an empty message send either
an empty [:String:] or an empty [:List<int>:]. [:null:] cannot be sent.

children.name: close
children.comment:
Close the web socket connection. The default value for [status]
and [reason] are [:null:].

children.name: WebSocketClientConnection
children.comment:
Creates a new web socket client connection based on a HTTP(S) client
connection. The HTTP or HTTPS client connection must be freshly opened.
Client web socket connection.

children.name: WebSocketConnection
onMessage=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when a message has been
received. The type on [message] is either [:String:] or
[:List<int>:] depending on whether it is a text or binary
message. If the message is empty [message] will be [:null:].
If [message] is a [:List<int>:] then it will contain byte values
from 0 to 255.

children.name: onClosed=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when the web socket connection is
closed. [status] indicate the reason for closing. For network
errors the value of [status] will be
WebSocketStatus.ABNORMAL_CLOSURE]. In this callback it is
possible to call [close] if [close] has not already been called.
If [close] has still not been called after the close callback
returns the received close status will automatically be echoed
back to the other end to finish the close handshake.

children.name: send
children.comment:
Sends a message. The [message] must be a [:String:], a
[:List<int>:] containing bytes, or [:null:].

children.name: close
children.comment:
Close the web socket connection. The default value for [status]
and [reason] are [:null:].
Server web socket connection.

children.name: WebSocketHandler
onRequest
children.comment: Request handler to be registered with the HTTP server.

children.name: onOpen=
children.comment:
Sets the callback to be called when a new web socket connection
has been established.

children.name: WebSocketStatus
children.comment: Web socket status codes used when closing a web socket connection.

children.name: close
children.comment: Closes the socket.

children.name: port
children.comment: Returns the port used by this socket.

children.name: SecureServerSocket
children.comment:
Constructs a new secure server socket, binds it to a given address
and port, and listens on it.  Incoming client connections are
promoted to secure connections, using the server certificate given by
certificate_name.  The bindAddress must be given as a numeric address,
not a host name.  The certificate name is the distinguished name (DN) of
the certificate, such as "CN=localhost" or "CN=myserver.mydomain.com".
The certificate is looked up in the NSS certificate database set by
SecureSocket.setCertificateDatabase.

To request or require that clients authenticate by providing an SSL (TLS)
client certificate, set the optional parameters requestClientCertificate or
requireClientCertificate to true.  Require implies request, so one doesn't
need to specify both.  To check whether a client certificate was received,
check SecureSocket.peerCertificate after connecting.  If no certificate
was received, the result will be null.

children.name: X509Certificate
children.comment:
X509Certificate represents an SSL certificate, with accessors to
get the fields of the certificate.

children.name: SecureSocket
onBadCertificate=
children.comment:
Install a handler for unverifiable certificates.  The handler can inspect
the certificate, and decide (or let the user decide) whether to accept
the connection or not.  The callback should return true
to continue the SecureSocket connection.

children.name: initialize
children.comment:
Initializes the NSS library.  If [initialize] is not called, the library
is automatically initialized as if [initialize] were called with no
arguments.

The optional argument [database] is the path to a certificate database
containing root certificates for verifying certificate paths on
client connections, and server certificates to provide on server
connections.  The argument [password] should be used when creating
secure server sockets, to allow the private key of the server
certificate to be fetched.  If [useBuiltinRoots] is true (the default),
then a built-in set of root certificates for trusted certificate
authorities is merged with the certificates in the database.

Examples:
  1) Use only the builtin root certificates:
    SecureSocket.initialize(); or

  2) Use a specified database and the builtin roots:
    SecureSocket.initialize(database: 'path/to/my/database',
                            password: 'my_password');

  3) Use a specified database, without builtin roots:
    SecureSocket.initialize(database: 'path/to/my/database',
                            password: 'my_password'.
                            useBuiltinRoots: false);

The database should be an NSS certificate database directory
containing a cert9.db file, not a cert8.db file.  This version of
the database can be created using the NSS certutil tool with "sql:" in
front of the absolute path of the database directory, or setting the
environment variable [[NSS_DEFAULT_DB_TYPE]] to "sql".

children.name: peerCertificate
children.comment:
Get the peerCertificate for a connected secure socket.  For a server
socket, this will return the client certificate, or null, if no
client certificate was received.  For a client socket, this
will return the server's certificate.

children.name: SecureSocket
children.comment:
Constructs a new secure client socket and connect it to the given
host on the given port. The returned socket is not yet connected
but ready for registration of callbacks.  If sendClientCertificate is
set to true, the socket will send a client certificate if one is
requested by the server.  If clientCertificate is the nickname of
a certificate in the certificate database, that certificate will be sent.
If clientCertificate is null, which is the usual use case, an
appropriate certificate will be searched for in the database and
sent automatically, based on what the server says it will accept.

SecureSocket provides a secure (SSL or TLS) client connection to a server.
The certificate provided by the server is checked
using the certificate database (optionally) provided in initialize().

children.name: available
children.comment:
Returns the number of received and non-read bytes in the socket that
can be read.

children.name: read
children.comment:
Read up to [len] bytes from the socket. This function is
non-blocking and will only return data if data is available. The
number of bytes read can be less then [len] if fewer bytes are
available for immediate reading. If no data is available [null]
is returned.

children.name: readList
children.comment:
Reads up to [count] bytes of data from the socket and stores them into
buffer after buffer offset [offset]. The number of successfully read
bytes is returned. This function is non-blocking and will only read data
if data is available.

children.name: writeList
children.comment:
Writes up to [count] bytes of the buffer from [offset] buffer offset to
the socket. The number of successfully written bytes is returned. This
function is non-blocking and will only write data if buffer space is
available in the socket.

children.name: onConnect=
children.comment:
The connect handler gets called when connection to a given host
succeeded.

children.name: onData=
children.comment: The data handler gets called when data becomes available at the socket.

children.name: onWrite=
children.comment:
The write handler gets called once when the socket becomes
available for writing. Then the handler is automatically reset to null.
This handler is mainly used when writeList has reported an incomplete
write, to schedule writing the remaining data to the socket.

children.name: onClosed=
children.comment:
The close handler gets called when a the last byte have been read
from a socket. At this point the socket might still be open for
writing for sending more data.

children.name: onError=
children.comment: The error handler gets called when a socket error occurs.

children.name: close
children.comment:
Closes the socket. Calling [close] will never throw an exception
and calling it several times is supported. If [halfClose] is true
the socket will only be closed for writing and it might still be
possible to read data. Calling [close] will not trigger a call to
[onClosed].

children.name: inputStream
children.comment: Returns input stream to the socket.

children.name: outputStream
children.comment: Returns output stream of the socket.

children.name: port
children.comment: Returns the port used by this socket.

children.name: remotePort
children.comment: Returns the remote port connected to by this socket.

children.name: remoteHost
children.comment: Returns the remote host connected to by this socket.

children.name: Socket
children.comment:
Constructs a new socket and initiate connecting it to the given
host on the given port. The returned socket is not yet connected
but ready for registration of callbacks.

children.name: onConnection=
children.comment:
The connection handler gets called when there is a new incoming
connection on the socket.

children.name: onError=
children.comment: The error handler gets called when a socket error occurs.

children.name: close
children.comment: Closes the socket.

children.name: port
children.comment: Returns the port used by this socket.

children.name: ServerSocket
children.comment:
Constructs a new server socket, binds it to a given address and port,
and listens on it.

children.name: ProcessSignal
children.comment:
On Posix systems, [ProcessSignal] is used to send a specific signal
to a child process, see [:Process.kill:].

children.name: ProcessOptions
children.comment:
[ProcessOptions] represents the options that can be supplied when
starting a process.

children.name: ProcessResult
exitCode
children.comment: Exit code for the process.

children.name: stdout
children.comment: Standard output from the process as a string.

children.name: stderr
children.comment: Standard error from the process as a string.

[ProcessResult] represents the result of running a non-interactive
process started with [:Process.run:].

children.name: Process
start
children.comment:
Starts a process running the [executable] with the specified
[arguments]. Returns a [:Future<Process>:] that completes with a
Process instance when the process has been successfully
started. That [Process] object can be used to interact with the
process. If the process cannot be started the returned [Future]
completes with an exception.

An optional [ProcessOptions] object can be passed to specify
options other than the executable and the arguments.

Users must read all data coming on the [stdout] and [stderr]
streams of processes started with [:Process.start:]. If the user
does not read all data on the streams the underlying system
resources will not be freed since there is still pending data.

children.name: run
children.comment:
Starts a process and runs it non-interactively to completion. The
process run is [executable] with the specified [arguments].

An optional [ProcessOptions] object can be passed to specify
options other than the executable and the arguments.

Returns a [:Future<ProcessResult>:] that completes with the
result of running the process, i.e., exit code, standard out and
standard in.

children.name: onExit=
children.comment:
Sets an exit handler which gets invoked when the process
terminates.

Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the process is
non-interactive.

children.name: kill
children.comment:
On Windows, [kill] kills the process, ignoring the [signal]
flag. On Posix systems, [kill] sends [signal] to the
process. Depending on the signal giving, it'll have different
meanings. When the process terminates as a result of calling
[kill] [onExit] is called.

Returns [:true:] if the process is successfully killed (the
signal is successfully sent). Returns [:false:] if the process
could not be killed (the signal could not be sent). Usually,
a [:false:] return value from kill means that the process is
already dead.

children.name: stdout
children.comment:
Returns an input stream of the process stdout.

Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the process is
non-interactive.

children.name: stderr
children.comment:
Returns an input stream of the process stderr.

Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the process is
non-interactive.

children.name: stdin
children.comment:
Returns an output stream to the process stdin.

Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the process is
non-interactive.

[Process] is used to start new processes using the static
[start] and [run] methods.

children.name: Platform
numberOfProcessors
children.comment: Get the number of processors of the machine.

children.name: pathSeparator
children.comment:
Get the path separator used by the operating system to separate
components in file paths.

children.name: operatingSystem
children.comment:
Get a string ('macos', 'windows', 'linux') representing the
operating system.

children.name: localHostname
children.comment: Get the local hostname for the system.

children.name: environment
children.comment:
Get the environment for this process.

Environment variables on Windows are case-insensitive. The map
returned on Windows is therefore case-insensitive and will convert
all keys to upper case. On other platforms the returned map is
a standard case-sensitive map.

The [Platform] class exposes details of the machine and operating
system.

children.name: Path
canonicalize
children.comment:
Make a path canonical by dropping segments that are '.', cancelling
segments that are '..' with preceding segments, if possible,
and combining consecutive '/'s.  Leading '..' segments
are kept on relative paths, and dropped from absolute paths.

children.name: join
children.comment:
Joins the relative path [further] to this path.  Canonicalizes the
resulting joined path using [canonicalize],
interpreting '.' and '..' as directory traversal commands, and removing
consecutive '/'s.

If [further] is an absolute path, an IllegalArgument exception is thrown.

Examples:
  `new Path('/a/b/c').join(new Path('d/e'))` returns the Path object
  containing `'a/b/c/d/e'`.

  `new Path('a/b/../c/').join(new Path('d/./e//')` returns the Path
  containing `'a/c/d/e/'`.

  `new Path('a/b/c').join(new Path('d/../../e')` returns the Path
  containing `'a/b/e'`.

Note that the join operation does not drop the last segment of the
base path, the way URL joining does.  To join basepath to further using
URL semantics, use
   [:basepath.directoryPath.join(further):].

If you want to avoid joins that traverse
parent directories in the base, you can check whether
`further.canonicalize()` starts with '../' or equals '..'.

children.name: relativeTo
children.comment:
Returns a path [:relative:] such that
   [:base.join(relative) == this.canonicalize():].
Throws an exception if such a path is impossible.
For example, if [base] is '../../a/b' and [this] is '.'.
The computation is independent of the file system and current directory.

To compute a relative path using URL semantics, where the final
path component of the base is dropped unless it ends with a slash,
call [: a.relativeTo(b.directoryPath) :] instead of [: a.relativeTo(b) :].

children.name: toNativePath
children.comment:
Converts a path to a string using the native filesystem's conventions.

On Windows, converts '/'s to backwards slashes, and removes
the leading '/' if the path starts with a drive specification.
For most valid Windows paths, this should be the inverse of the
conversion that the constructor new Path() performs.  If the path is
a Windows share, restores the '\\' at the start of the path.

children.name: toString
children.comment:
Returns the path as a string.  If this path is constructed using
new Path.raw(), or new Path() on a non-Windows system, the
returned value is the original string argument to the constructor.

children.name: segments
append
children.comment:
Appends [finalSegment] to a path as a new segment.  Adds a '/'
between the path and [finalSegment] if the path does not already end in
a '/'.  The path is not canonicalized, and [finalSegment] may
contain '/'s.

children.name: isEmpty
children.comment: Is this path the empty string?

children.name: isAbsolute
children.comment:
Is this path an absolute path, beginning with a '/'?  Note that
Windows paths beginning with '\' or with a drive letter are absolute,
and a leading '/' is added when they are converted to a Path.

children.name: isWindowsShare
children.comment: Is this path a Windows share path?

children.name: hasTrailingSeparator
children.comment: Does this path end with a '/'?

children.name: isCanonical
children.comment:
Does this path contain no consecutive '/'s, no segments that
are '.' unless the path is exactly '.', and segments that are '..' only
as the leading segments on a relative path?

children.name: directoryPath
children.comment:
Drops the final '/' and whatever follows it from this Path,
and returns the resulting Path object.  If the only '/' in
this Path is the first character, returns '/' instead of the empty string.
If there is no '/' in the Path, returns the empty string.

    new Path('../images/dot.gif').directoryPath == '../images'
    new Path('/usr/geoffrey/www/').directoryPath == '/usr/geoffrey/www'
    new Path('lost_file_old').directoryPath == ''
    new Path('/src').directoryPath == '/'
    Note: new Path('/D:/src').directoryPath == '/D:'

children.name: filename
children.comment:
The part of the path after the last '/', or the entire path if
it contains no '/'.

    new Path('images/DSC_0027.jpg).filename == 'DSC_0027.jpg'
    new Path('users/fred/').filename == ''

children.name: filenameWithoutExtension
children.comment:
The part of [filename] before the last '.', or the entire filename if it
contains no '.'.  If [filename] is '.' or '..' it is unchanged.

    new Path('/c:/My Documents/Heidi.txt').filenameWithoutExtension
    would return 'Heidi'.
    new Path('not what I would call a path').filenameWithoutExtension
    would return 'not what I would call a path'.

children.name: extension
children.comment:
The part of [filename] after the last '.', or '' if [filename]
contains no '.'.  If [filename] is '.' or '..', returns ''.

    new Path('tiger.svg').extension == 'svg'
    new Path('/src/dart/dart_secrets').extension == ''

children.name: Path
children.comment:
Creates a Path from a String that uses the native filesystem's conventions.

On Windows, this converts '\' to '/' and has special handling for drive
letters and shares.

If the path starts with a drive letter, like 'C:',  a '/' is added
before the drive letter.

    new Path(r'c:\a\b').toString() == '/c:/a/b'

A path starting with a drive letter is
treated specially.  Backwards links ('..') cannot cancel the drive letter.

If the path is a share path this is recorded in the Path object and
maintained in operations on the Path object.

    var share = new Path(r'\\share\a\b\c');
    share.isWindowsShare == true
    share.toString() == '/share/a/b/c'
    share.toNativePath() == r'\\share\a\b\c'
    share.append('final').isWindowsShare == true

children.name: Path.raw
children.comment:
Creates a Path from the String [source].  [source] is used as-is, so if
the string does not consist of segments separated by forward slashes, the
behavior may not be as expected.  Paths are immutable.

A Path is an immutable wrapper of a String, with additional member functions
for useful path manipulations and queries.
On the Windows platform, Path also converts from native paths to paths using
'/' as a path separator, and vice versa.

Joining of paths and path normalization handle '.' and '..' in the usual way.

children.name: OutputStream
write
children.comment:
Writes the content of [buffer] to the stream. If [copyBuffer] is
false ownership of the specified buffer is passed to the system
and the caller should not change it afterwards. The default value
for [copyBuffer] is true.

Returns true if the data could be written to the underlying
communication channel immediately. Otherwise the data is buffered
by the output stream and will be sent as soon as possible.

children.name: writeFrom
children.comment:
Writes [len] bytes from buffer [buffer] starting at offset
[offset] to the output stream. If [offset] is not specified the
default is 0. If [len] is not specified the default is the length
of the buffer minus [offset] (i.e. writing from offset to the end
of the buffer). The system will copy the data to be written so
the caller can safely change [buffer] afterwards.

Returns true if the data could be written to the underlying
communication channel immediately. Otherwise the data is buffered
by the output stream and will be sent as soon as possible.

children.name: writeString
children.comment:
Write a string to the stream using the given [encoding].The
default encoding is UTF-8 - [:Encoding.UTF_8:].

Returns true if the data could be written to the underlying
communication channel immediately. Otherwise the data is buffered
by the output stream and will be sent as soon as possible.

children.name: flush
children.comment:
Flushes data from any internal buffers as soon as possible. Note
that the actual meaning of calling [flush] will depend on the
actual type of the underlying communication channel.

children.name: close
children.comment:
Signal that no more data will be written to the output stream. When all
buffered data has been written out to the communication channel, the
channel will be closed and the [onClosed] callback will be called.

children.name: destroy
children.comment:
Close the communication channel immediately ignoring any buffered
data.

children.name: onNoPendingWrites=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when the internal OS buffers
have been flushed. This callback can be used to keep the rate of
writing in sync with the rate the system can write data to the
underlying communication channel.

children.name: onClosed=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when the underlying communication channel
has been closed and all the buffered data has been sent.

children.name: onError=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when the underlying
communication channel gets into some kind of error situation.

children.name: closed
children.comment:
Returns whether the stream has been closed by calling close(). If true, no
more data may be written to the output stream, but there still may be
buffered data that has not been written to the communication channel. The
onClosed handler will only be called once all data has been written out.

Output streams are used to write data sequentially to a data
destination e.g. a connected socket or an open file.

An output stream provides internal buffering of the data written
through all calls to [write] and [writeFrom] if data cannot be
written immediately to the communication channel. The callback set
through [onNoPendingWrites] can be used to to keep the rate of
writing in sync with the rate the system can actually write data to
the underlying communication channel.

children.name: _MimeMultipartParser
_ListInputStream
children.comment: Default implementation of [ListInputStream].

children.name: ListOutputStream
read
children.comment:
Reads all available data from the stream. If no data is available `null`
will be returned.

children.name: onData=
children.comment: Sets the handler that gets called when data is available.

children.name: ListOutputStream
children.comment: Create a [ListOutputStream].

[ListOutputStream] makes it possible to use the [OutputStream]
interface to write data to a [List] of integers.

children.name: ListInputStream
write
children.comment: Write more data to be streamed over to the [ListInputStream].

children.name: markEndOfStream
children.comment:
Notify the [ListInputStream] that no more data will be written to
it.

children.name: ListInputStream
children.comment:
Create an empty [ListInputStream] to which data can be written
using the [write] method.

[ListInputStream] makes it possible to use the [InputStream]
interface to stream over data that is received in chunks as lists
of integers.

When a new list of integers is received it can be written to the
[ListInputStream] using the [write] method. The [markEndOfStream]
method must be called when the last data has been written to the
[ListInputStream].

children.name: ChunkedInputStream
read
children.comment:
Reads [chunkSize] bytes from the stream. If [chunkSize] bytes are
not currently available null is returned. When the stream is
closed the last call can return with less than [chunkSize] bytes.

children.name: chunkSize=
children.comment: Sets the chunk size used by this stream.

children.name: onData=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when at least [chunkSize] bytes
of data is available or the underlying stream has been closed and
there is still unread data.

children.name: onClosed=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when there will be no more data
available in the stream.

children.name: onError=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when the underlying
communication channel gets into some kind of error situation.

children.name: closed
children.comment:
Returns whether the stream has been closed. There might still be
more data to read.

children.name: chunkSize
children.comment: Returns the chunk size used by this stream.

children.name: ChunkedInputStream
children.comment:
Adds buffering to an input stream and provide the ability to read
the data in known size chunks.

A chunked input stream wraps a basic input stream and supplies
binary data in configurable chunk sizes.

children.name: StringInputStream
read
children.comment:
Reads up to [len] characters from the stream. if [len] is not
specified reads as many characters as is available from the
stream. If no data is available null will be returned.

children.name: readLine
children.comment:
Reads the next line from the stream. The line ending characters
will not be part of the returned string. If a full line is not
available null will be returned.

children.name: available
children.comment:
Returns the number of characters available for immediate
reading. Note that this includes all characters that will be in
the String returned from [read] this includes line breaking
characters. If [readLine] is used for reading one can observe
less characters being returned as the line breaking characters
are discarded.

children.name: onData=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when data is available. The two
handlers [onData] and [onLine] are mutually exclusive
and setting one will remove the other.

children.name: onLine=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when a line is available. The
two handlers [onData] and [onLine] are mutually
exclusive and setting one will remove the other.

children.name: onClosed=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when there will be no more data
available in the stream.

children.name: onError=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when the underlying
communication channel gets into some kind of error situation.

children.name: closed
children.comment:
Returns whether the stream has been closed. There might still be
more data to read.

children.name: encoding
children.comment: Returns the encoding used to decode the binary data into characters.

children.name: StringInputStream
children.comment:
Decodes a binary input stream into characters using the specified
encoding.

A string input stream wraps a basic input stream and supplies
string data. This data can be read either as string chunks or as
lines separated by line termination character sequences.

children.name: Encoding
children.comment: String encodings.

children.name: InputStream
read
children.comment:
Reads data from the stream. Returns a system allocated buffer
with up to [len] bytes. If no value is passed for [len] all
available data will be returned. If no data is available null will
be returned.

children.name: readInto
children.comment:
Reads up to [len] bytes into buffer [buffer] starting at offset
[offset]. Returns the number of bytes actually read which might
be zero. If [offset] is not specified 0 is used. If [len] is not
specified the length of [buffer] is used.

children.name: available
children.comment: Returns the number of bytes available for immediate reading.

children.name: pipe
children.comment:
Pipe the content of this input stream directly to the output
stream [output]. The default behavior is to close the output when
all the data from the input stream have been written. Specifying
`false` for the optional argument [close] keeps the output
stream open after writing all data from the input stream.

children.name: close
children.comment:
Close the underlying communication channel to avoid getting any
more data. In normal situations, where all data is read from the
stream until the close handler is called, calling [close] is not
required. When [close] is used the close handler will still be
called.

children.name: onData=
children.comment: Sets the handler that gets called when data is available.

children.name: onClosed=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when there will be no more data
available in the stream.

children.name: onError=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called when the underlying
communication channel gets into some kind of error situation.

children.name: closed
children.comment:
Returns whether the stream is closed. There will be no more data
to read.

Basic input stream which supplies binary data.

Input streams are used to read data sequentially from some data
source. All input streams are non-blocking. They each have a number
of read calls which will always return without any IO related
blocking. If the requested data is not available a read call will
return `null`. All input streams have one or more handlers which
will trigger when data is available.

The following example shows a data handler in an ordinary input
stream which will be called when some data is available and a call
to read will not return `null`.

    InputStream input = ...
    input.onData = () {
      var data = input.read();
      ...
    };

If for some reason the data from an input stream cannot be handled
by the application immediately setting the data handler to `null`
will avoid further callbacks until it is set to a function
again. While the data handler is not active system flow control
will be used to avoid buffering more data than needed.

Always set up appropriate handlers when using input streams.

children.name: _HttpParser
children.comment:
HTTP parser which parses the HTTP stream as data is supplied
through the [:streamData:] and [:streamDone:] methods. As the
data is parsed the following callbacks are called:

  [:requestStart:]
  [:responseStart:]
  [:dataReceived:]
  [:dataEnd:]
  [:closed:]
  [:error:]

If an HTTP parser error occours it is possible to get an exception
thrown from the [:streamData:] and [:streamDone:] methods if
the error callback is not set.

The connection upgrades (e.g. switching from HTTP/1.1 to the
WebSocket protocol) is handled in a special way. If connection
upgrade is specified in the headers, then on the callback to
[:responseStart:] the [:upgrade:] property on the [:HttpParser:]
object will be [:true:] indicating that from now on the protocol is
not HTTP anymore and no more callbacks will happen, that is
[:dataReceived:] and [:dataEnd:] are not called in this case as
there is no more HTTP data. After the upgrade the method
[:readUnparsedData:] can be used to read any remaining bytes in the
HTTP parser which are part of the protocol the connection is
upgrading to. These bytes cannot be processed by the HTTP parser
and should be handled according to whatever protocol is being
upgraded to.

children.name: DetachedSocket
children.comment:
When detaching a socket from either the [:HttpServer:] or the
[:HttpClient:] due to a HTTP connection upgrade there might be
unparsed data already read from the socket. This unparsed data
together with the detached socket is returned in an instance of
this class.

children.name: RedirectInfo
statusCode
children.comment: Returns the status code used for the redirect.

children.name: method
children.comment: Returns the method used for the redirect.

children.name: location
children.comment: Returns the location for the redirect.
Redirect information.

children.name: HttpConnectionInfo
children.comment: Connection information.

children.name: HttpClientDigestCredentials
children.comment: Represent credentials for digest authentication.

children.name: HttpClientBasicCredentials
children.comment: Represent credentials for basic authentication.

children.name: HttpClientResponse
statusCode
children.comment: Returns the status code.

children.name: reasonPhrase
children.comment: Returns the reason phrase associated with the status code.

children.name: contentLength
children.comment:
Returns the content length of the request body. If the size of
the request body is not known in advance this -1.

children.name: persistentConnection
children.comment: Gets the persistent connection state returned by the server.

children.name: isRedirect
children.comment:
Returns whether the status code is one of the normal redirect
codes [:HttpStatus.MOVED_PERMANENTLY:], [:HttpStatus.FOUND:],
[:HttpStatus.MOVED_TEMPORARILY:], [:HttpStatus.SEE_OTHER:] and
[:HttpStatus.TEMPORARY_REDIRECT:].

children.name: headers
children.comment: Returns the response headers.

children.name: cookies
children.comment: Cookies set by the server (from the Set-Cookie header).

children.name: certificate
children.comment:
Returns the certificate of the HTTPS server providing the response.
Returns null if the connection is not a secure TLS or SSL connection.

children.name: inputStream
children.comment:
Returns the input stream for the response. This is used to read
the response data.
HTTP response for a client connection.

children.name: HttpClientRequest
headers
children.comment: Returns the request headers.

children.name: cookies
children.comment: Cookies to present to the server (in the Cookie header).

children.name: outputStream
children.comment:
Returns the output stream for the request. This is used to write
the request data. When all request data has been written close
the stream to indicate the end of the request.

When this is accessed for the first time the request header is
send. Calling any methods that will change the header after
having retrieved the output stream will throw an exception.
HTTP request for a client connection.

children.name: HttpClientConnection
onRequest=
children.comment: Sets the handler that is called when the connection is established.

children.name: onResponse=
children.comment:
Sets callback to be called when the request has been send and
the response is ready for processing. The callback is called when
all headers of the response are received and data is ready to be
received.

children.name: onError=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that gets called if an error occurs while
connecting or processing the HTTP request.

children.name: redirect
children.comment:
Redirect this connection to a new URL. The default value for
[method] is the method for the current request. The default value
for [url] is the value of the [:HttpHeaders.LOCATION:] header of
the current response. All body data must have been read from the
current response before calling [redirect].

All headers added to the request will be added to the redirection
request(s). However, any body send with the request will not be
part of the redirection request(s).

children.name: detachSocket
children.comment:
Detach the underlying socket from the HTTP client. When the
socket is detached the HTTP client will no longer perform any
operations on it.

This is normally used when a HTTP upgrade is negotiated and the
communication should continue with a different protocol.

children.name: redirects
children.comment: Returns the series of redirects this connection has been through.

children.name: connectionInfo
children.comment:
Get information about the client connection. Returns [null] if the socket
isn't available.

A [HttpClientConnection] is returned by all [HttpClient] methods
that initiate a connection to an HTTP server. The handlers will be
called as the connection state progresses.

The setting of all handlers is optional. If [onRequest] is not set
the request will be send without any additional headers and an
empty body. If [onResponse] is not set the response will be read
and discarded.

children.name: HttpClient
open
children.comment:
Opens a HTTP connection. The returned [HttpClientConnection] is
used to register callbacks for asynchronous events on the HTTP
connection. The "Host" header for the request will be set to the
value [host]:[port]. This can be overridden through the
HttpClientRequest interface before the request is sent. NOTE if
[host] is an IP address this will still be set in the "Host"
header.

children.name: openUrl
children.comment:
Opens a HTTP connection. The returned [HttpClientConnection] is
used to register callbacks for asynchronous events on the HTTP
connection. The "Host" header for the request will be set based
the host and port specified in [url]. This can be overridden
through the HttpClientRequest interface before the request is
sent. NOTE if the host is specified as an IP address this will
still be set in the "Host" header.

children.name: get
children.comment:
Opens a HTTP connection using the GET method. See [open] for
details. Using this method to open a HTTP connection will set the
content length to 0.

children.name: getUrl
children.comment:
Opens a HTTP connection using the GET method. See [openUrl] for
details. Using this method to open a HTTP connection will set the
content length to 0.

children.name: post
children.comment: Opens a HTTP connection using the POST method. See [open] for details.

children.name: postUrl
children.comment: Opens a HTTP connection using the POST method. See [openUrl] for details.

children.name: authenticate=
children.comment:
Sets the function to be called when a site is requesting
authentication. The URL requested and the security realm from the
server are passed in the arguments [url] and [realm].

The function returns a [Future] which should complete when the
authentication has been resolved. If credentials cannot be
provided the [Future] should complete with [false]. If
credentials are available the function should add these using
[addCredentials] before completing the [Future] with the value
[true].

If the [Future] completes with true the request will be retried
using the updated credentials. Otherwise response processing will
continue normally.

children.name: addCredentials
children.comment: Add credentials to be used for authorizing HTTP requests.

children.name: sendClientCertificate=
children.comment:
If [sendClientCertificate] is set to true, authenticate with a client
certificate when connecting with an HTTPS server that requests one.
Select the certificate from the certificate database that matches
the authorities listed by the HTTPS server as valid.
If [clientCertificate] is set, send the certificate with that nickname
instead.

children.name: clientCertificate=
children.comment:
If [clientCertificate] is non-null and [sendClientCertificate] is true,
use [clientCertificate] to select the certificate to send from the
certificate database, looking it up by its nickname.

children.name: findProxy=
children.comment:
Sets the function used to resolve the proxy server to be used for
opening a HTTP connection to the specified [url]. If this
function is not set, direct connections will always be used.

The string returned by [f] must be in the format used by browser
PAC (proxy auto-config) scripts. That is either

  "DIRECT"

for using a direct connection or

  "PROXY host:port"

for using the proxy server [:host:] on port [:port:].

A configuration can contain several configuration elements
separated by semicolons, e.g.

  "PROXY host:port; PROXY host2:port2; DIRECT"

children.name: shutdown
children.comment:
Shutdown the HTTP client. If [force] is [:false:] (the default)
the [:HttpClient:] will be kept alive until all active
connections are done. If [force] is [:true:] any active
connections will be closed to immediately release all
resources. These closed connections will receive an [:onError:]
callback to indicate that the client was shutdown. In both cases
trying to establish a new connection after calling [shutdown]
will throw an exception.

HTTP client factory. The [HttpClient] handles all the sockets associated
with the [HttpClientConnection]s and when the endpoint supports it, it will
try to reuse opened sockets for several requests to support HTTP 1.1
persistent connections. This means that sockets will be kept open for some
time after a requests have completed, unless HTTP procedures indicate that it
must be closed as part of completing the request. Use [:HttpClient.shutdown:]
to force close the idle sockets.

children.name: HttpResponse
detachSocket
children.comment:
Detach the underlying socket from the HTTP server. When the
socket is detached the HTTP server will no longer perform any
operations on it.

This is normally used when a HTTP upgrade request is received
and the communication should continue with a different protocol.

children.name: headers
children.comment: Returns the response headers.

children.name: cookies
children.comment: Cookies to set in the client (in the Set-Cookie header).

children.name: outputStream
children.comment:
Returns the output stream for the response. This is used to write
the response data. When all response data has been written close
the stream to indicate the end of the response.

When this is accessed for the first time the response header is
send. Calling any methods that will change the header after
having retrieved the output stream will throw an exception.

children.name: connectionInfo
children.comment:
Get information about the client connection. Returns [null] if the socket
isn't available.
HTTP response to be send back to the client.

children.name: HttpRequest
session
children.comment:
Returns, or initialize, a session for the given request. If the session is
being initialized by this call, [init] will be called with the
newly create session. Here the [:HttpSession.data:] field can be set, if
needed.
See [:HttpServer.sessionTimeout:] on how to change default timeout.

children.name: contentLength
children.comment:
Returns the content length of the request body. If the size of
the request body is not known in advance this -1.

children.name: persistentConnection
children.comment: Returns the persistent connection state signaled by the client.

children.name: method
children.comment: Returns the method for the request.

children.name: uri
children.comment: Returns the URI for the request.

children.name: path
children.comment: Returns the path part of the URI.

children.name: queryString
children.comment: Returns the query string.

children.name: queryParameters
children.comment: Returns the parsed query string.

children.name: headers
children.comment: Returns the request headers.

children.name: cookies
children.comment: Returns the cookies in the request (from the Cookie headers).

children.name: certificate
children.comment:
Returns the client certificate of the client making the request.
Returns null if the connection is not a secure TLS or SSL connection,
or if the server does not request a client certificate, or if the client
does not provide one.

children.name: inputStream
children.comment:
Returns the input stream for the request. This is used to read
the request data.

children.name: protocolVersion
children.comment:
Returns the HTTP protocol version used in the request. This will
be "1.0" or "1.1".

children.name: connectionInfo
children.comment:
Get information about the client connection. Returns [null] if the socket
isn't available.
Http request delivered to the HTTP server callback.

children.name: Cookie
toString
children.comment:
Returns the formatted string representation of the cookie. The
string representation can be used for for setting the Cookie or
Set-Cookie headers

children.name: Cookie
children.comment: Creates a new cookie optionally setting the name and value.

children.name: Cookie.fromSetCookieValue
children.comment:
Creates a new cookie by parsing a header value from a Set-Cookie
header.

Representation of a cookie. For cookies received by the server as
Cookie header values only [:name:] and [:value:] fields will be
set. When building a cookie for the Set-Cookie header in the server
and when receiving cookies in the client as Set-Cookie headers all
fields can be used.

children.name: ContentType
ContentType
children.comment:
Creates a new content type object setting the primary type and
sub type.

children.name: ContentType.fromString
children.comment:
Creates a new content type object from parsing a Content-Type
header value. As primary type, sub type and parameter names and
values are not case sensitive all these values will be converted
to lower case. Parsing this string

    text/html; charset=utf-8

will create a content type object with primary type [:text:], sub
type [:html:] and parameter [:charset:] with value [:utf-8:].
Representation of a content type.

children.name: destroy
children.comment:
Destroy the session. This will terminate the session and any further
connections with this id will be given a new id and session.

children.name: onTimeout=
children.comment: Set a callback that will be called when the session is timed out.

children.name: id
children.comment: Get the id for the current session.

children.name: HeaderValue
toString
children.comment:
Returns the formatted string representation in the form:

    value; parameter1=value1; parameter2=value2

children.name: parameters
children.comment: Gets the map of parameters.

children.name: HeaderValue
children.comment: Creates a new header value object setting the value part.

children.name: HeaderValue.fromString
children.comment:
Creates a new header value object from parsing a header value
string with both value and optional parameters.

children.name: HttpHeaders

children.comment:
Returns the list of values for the header named [name]. If there
is no headers with the provided name [:null:] will be returned.

children.name: value
children.comment:
Convenience method for the value for a single values header. If
there is no header with the provided name [:null:] will be
returned. If the header has more than one value an exception is
thrown.

children.name: add
children.comment:
Adds a header value. The header named [name] will have the value
[value] added to its list of values. Some headers are single
values and for these adding a value will replace the previous
value. If the value is of type DateTime a HTTP date format will be
applied. If the value is a [:List:] each element of the list will
be added separately. For all other types the default [:toString:]
method will be used.

children.name: set
children.comment:
Sets a header. The header named [name] will have all its values
cleared before the value [value] is added as its value.

children.name: remove
children.comment:
Removes a specific value for a header name. Some headers have
system supplied values and for these the system supplied values
will still be added to the collection of values for the header.

children.name: removeAll
children.comment:
Remove all values for the specified header name. Some headers
have system supplied values and for these the system supplied
values will still be added to the collection of values for the
header.

children.name: forEach
children.comment:
Enumerate the headers applying the function [f] to each
header. The header name passed in [name] will be all lower
case.

children.name: noFolding
children.comment:
Disable folding for the header named [name] when sending the HTTP
header. By default, multiple header values are folded into a
single header line by separating the values with commas. The
Set-Cookie header has folding disabled by default.

Access to the HTTP headers for requests and responses. In some
situations the headers will be imutable and the mutating methods
will then throw exceptions.

For all operation on HTTP headers the header name is
case-insensitive.

children.name: HttpConnectionsInfo
children.comment: Overview information of the [:HttpServer:] socket connections.

children.name: HttpsServer
children.comment: HTTPS server.

children.name: HttpServer
listen
children.comment:
Start listening for HTTP requests on the specified [host] and
[port]. If a [port] of 0 is specified the server will choose an
ephemeral port. The optional argument [backlog] can be used to
specify the listen backlog for the underlying OS listen.
The optional arguments [certificate_name] and [requestClientCertificate]
are used by the HttpsServer class, which shares the same interface.
See [addRequestHandler] and [defaultRequestHandler] for
information on how incoming HTTP requests are handled.

children.name: listenOn
children.comment:
Attach the HTTP server to an existing [:ServerSocket:]. If the
[HttpServer] is closed, the [HttpServer] will just detach itself,
and not close [serverSocket].

children.name: addRequestHandler
children.comment:
Adds a request handler to the list of request handlers. The
function [matcher] is called with the request and must return
[:true:] if the [handler] should handle the request. The first
handler for which [matcher] returns [:true:] will be handed the
request.

children.name: defaultRequestHandler=
children.comment:
Sets the default request handler. This request handler will be
called if none of the request handlers registered by
[addRequestHandler] matches the current request. If no default
request handler is set the server will just respond with status
code [:NOT_FOUND:] (404).

children.name: close
children.comment: Stop server listening.

children.name: onError=
children.comment: Sets the error handler that is called when a connection error occurs.

children.name: sessionTimeout=
children.comment:
Set the timeout, in seconds, for sessions of this HTTP server. Default
is 20 minutes.

children.name: connectionsInfo
children.comment:
Returns a [:HttpConnectionsInfo:] object with an overview of the
current connection handled by the server.

children.name: port
children.comment:
Returns the port that the server is listening on. This can be
used to get the actual port used when a value of 0 for [port] is
specified in the [listen] call.
HTTP server.

children.name: HttpStatus
children.comment: HTTP status codes.

children.name: RandomAccessFile
close
children.comment:
Close the file. Returns a [:Future<RandomAccessFile>:] that
completes with this RandomAccessFile when it has been closed.

children.name: closeSync
children.comment: Synchronously close the file.

children.name: readByte
children.comment:
Read a byte from the file. Returns a [:Future<int>:] that
completes with the byte or -1 if end of file has been reached.

children.name: readByteSync
children.comment:
Synchronously read a single byte from the file. If end of file
has been reached -1 is returned.

children.name: read
children.comment: Reads from a file and returns the result as a list of bytes.

children.name: readSync
children.comment:
Synchronously reads from a file and returns the result in a
list of bytes.

children.name: readList
children.comment:
Read a List<int> from the file. Returns a [:Future<int>:] that
completes with an indication of how much was read.

children.name: readListSync
children.comment:
Synchronously read a List<int> from the file. Returns the number
of bytes read.

children.name: writeByte
children.comment:
Write a single byte to the file. Returns a
[:Future<RandomAccessFile>:] that completes with this
RandomAccessFile when the write completes.

children.name: writeByteSync
children.comment:
Synchronously write a single byte to the file. Returns the
number of bytes successfully written.

children.name: writeList
children.comment:
Write a List<int> to the file. Returns a
[:Future<RandomAccessFile>:] that completes with this
RandomAccessFile when the write completes.

children.name: writeListSync
children.comment:
Synchronously write a List<int> to the file. Returns the number
of bytes successfully written.

children.name: writeString
children.comment:
Write a string to the file using the given [encoding]. Returns a
[:Future<RandomAccessFile>:] that completes with this
RandomAccessFile when the write completes.

children.name: writeStringSync
children.comment:
Synchronously write a single string to the file using the given
[encoding]. Returns the number of characters successfully
written.

children.name: position
children.comment:
Get the current byte position in the file. Returns a
[:Future<int>:] that completes with the position.

children.name: positionSync
children.comment: Synchronously get the current byte position in the file.

children.name: setPosition
children.comment:
Set the byte position in the file. Returns a
[:Future<RandomAccessFile>:] that completes with this
RandomAccessFile when the position has been set.

children.name: setPositionSync
children.comment: Synchronously set the byte position in the file.

children.name: truncate
children.comment:
Truncate (or extend) the file to [length] bytes. Returns a
[:Future<RandomAccessFile>:] that completes with this
RandomAccessFile when the truncation has been performed.

children.name: truncateSync
children.comment: Synchronously truncate (or extend) the file to [length] bytes.

children.name: length
children.comment:
Get the length of the file. Returns a [:Future<int>:] that
completes with the length in bytes.

children.name: lengthSync
children.comment: Synchronously get the length of the file.

children.name: flush
children.comment:
Flush the contents of the file to disk. Returns a
[:Future<RandomAccessFile>:] that completes with this
RandomAccessFile when the flush operation completes.

children.name: flushSync
children.comment: Synchronously flush the contents of the file to disk.

children.name: toString
children.comment: Returns a human readable string for this File instance.

children.name: name
children.comment: Get the name of the file.

[RandomAccessFile] provides random access to the data in a
file. [RandomAccessFile] objects are obtained by calling the
[:open:] method on a [File] object.

children.name: File
exists
children.comment:
Check if the file exists. Does not block and returns a
[:Future<bool>:].

children.name: existsSync
children.comment: Synchronously check if the file exists.

children.name: create
children.comment:
Create the file. Returns a [:Future<File>:] that completes with
the file when it has been created.

Existing files are left untouched by create. Calling create on an
existing file might fail if there are restrictive permissions on
the file.

children.name: createSync
children.comment:
Synchronously create the file. Existing files are left untouched
by create. Calling create on an existing file might fail if there
are restrictive permissions on the file.

children.name: delete
children.comment:
Delete the file. Returns a [:Future<File>:] that completes with
the file when it has been deleted.

children.name: deleteSync
children.comment: Synchronously delete the file.

children.name: directory
children.comment:
Get a Directory object for the directory containing this
file. Returns a [:Future<Directory>:] that completes with the
directory.

children.name: directorySync
children.comment:
Synchronously get a Directory object for the directory containing
this file.

children.name: length
children.comment:
Get the length of the file. Returns a [:Future<int>:] that
completes with the length in bytes.

children.name: lengthSync
children.comment: Synchronously get the length of the file.

children.name: lastModified
children.comment:
Get the last-modified time of the file. Returns a
[:Future<DateTime>:] that completes with a [DateTime] object for the
modification date.

children.name: lastModifiedSync
children.comment:
Get the last-modified time of the file. Throws an exception
if the file does not exist.

children.name: open
children.comment:
Open the file for random access operations. Returns a
[:Future<RandomAccessFile>:] that completes with the opened
random access file. RandomAccessFiles must be closed using the
[close] method.

Files can be opened in three modes:

FileMode.READ: open the file for reading.

FileMode.WRITE: open the file for both reading and writing and
truncate the file to length zero. If the file does not exist the
file is created.

FileMode.APPEND: same as FileMode.WRITE except that the file is
not truncated.

children.name: openSync
children.comment:
Synchronously open the file for random access operations. The
result is a RandomAccessFile on which random access operations
can be performed. Opened RandomAccessFiles must be closed using
the [close] method.

See [open] for information on the [mode] argument.

children.name: fullPath
children.comment:
Get the canonical full path corresponding to the file name.
Returns a [:Future<String>:] that completes with the path.

children.name: fullPathSync
children.comment: Synchronously get the canonical full path corresponding to the file name.

children.name: openInputStream
children.comment:
Create a new independent input stream for the file. The file
input stream must be closed when no longer used to free up system
resources.

children.name: openOutputStream
children.comment:
Creates a new independent output stream for the file. The file
output stream must be closed when no longer used to free up
system resources.

An output stream can be opened in two modes:

FileMode.WRITE: create the stream and truncate the underlying
file to length zero.

FileMode.APPEND: create the stream and set the position to the end of
the underlying file.

children.name: readAsBytes
children.comment:
Read the entire file contents as a list of bytes. Returns a
[:Future<List<int>>:] that completes with the list of bytes that
is the contents of the file.

children.name: readAsBytesSync
children.comment: Synchronously read the entire file contents as a list of bytes.

children.name: readAsString
children.comment:
Read the entire file contents as a string using the given
[encoding].

Returns a [:Future<String>:] that completes with the string once
the file contents has been read.

children.name: readAsStringSync
children.comment:
Synchronously read the entire file contents as a string using the
given [encoding].

children.name: readAsLines
children.comment:
Read the entire file contents as lines of text using the give
[encoding].

Returns a [:Future<List<String>>:] that completes with the lines
once the file contents has been read.

children.name: readAsLinesSync
children.comment:
Synchronously read the entire file contents as lines of text
using the given [encoding].

children.name: writeAsBytes
children.comment:
Write a list of bytes to a file.

Opens the file, writes the list of bytes to it, and closes the file.
Returns a [:Future<File>:] that completes with this [File] object once
the entire operation has completed.

By default [writeAsBytes] creates the file for writing and truncates the
file if it already exists. In order to append the bytes to an existing
file pass [:FileMode.APPEND:] as the optional mode parameter.

children.name: writeAsBytesSync
children.comment:
Synchronously write a list of bytes to a file.

Opens the file, writes the list of bytes to it and closses the file.

By default [writeAsBytesSync] creates the file for writing and truncates
the file if it already exists. In order to append the bytes to an existing
file pass [:FileMode.APPEND:] as the optional mode parameter.

children.name: writeAsString
children.comment:
Write a string to a file.

Opens the file, writes the string in the given encoding, and closes the
file. Returns a [:Future<File>:] that completes with this [File] object
once the entire operation has completed.

By default [writeAsString] creates the file for writing and truncates the
file if it already exists. In order to append the bytes to an existing
file pass [:FileMode.APPEND:] as the optional mode parameter.

children.name: writeAsStringSync
children.comment:
Synchronously write a string to a file.

Opens the file, writes the string in the given encoding, and closes the
file.

By default [writeAsStringSync] creates the file for writing and
truncates the file if it already exists. In order to append the bytes
to an existing file pass [:FileMode.APPEND:] as the optional mode
parameter.

children.name: name
children.comment: Get the name of the file.

children.name: File
children.comment: Create a File object.

children.name: File.fromPath
children.comment: Create a File object from a Path object.

[File] objects are references to files.

To operate on the underlying file data you need to either get
streams using [openInputStream] and [openOutputStream] or open the
file for random access operations using [open].

children.name: FileMode
children.comment: FileMode describes the modes in which a file can be opened.

children.name: DirectoryLister
onDir=
children.comment:
Sets the directory handler that is called for all directories
during listing. The directory handler is called with the full
path of the directory.

children.name: onFile=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that is called for all files during listing. The
file handler is called with the full path of the file.

children.name: onDone=
children.comment:
Set the handler that is called when a listing is done. The
handler is called with an indication of whether or not the
listing operation completed.

children.name: onError=
children.comment:
Sets the handler that is called if there is an error while
listing directories.

A [DirectoryLister] represents an actively running listing operation.

A [DirectoryLister] is obtained from a [Directory] object by calling
the [:Directory.list:] method.

    Directory dir = new Directory('path/to/my/dir');
    DirectoryLister lister = dir.list();

For each file and directory, the file or directory handler is
called. When all directories have been listed the done handler is
called. If the listing operation is recursive, the error handler is
called if a subdirectory cannot be opened for listing.

children.name: Directory
exists
children.comment:
Check whether a directory with this name already exists. Returns
a [:Future<bool>:] that completes with the result.

children.name: existsSync
children.comment: Synchronously check whether a directory with this name already exists.

children.name: create
children.comment:
Creates the directory with this name.

If [recursive] is false, only the last directory in the path is
created. If [recursive] is true, all non-existing path components
are created. If the directory already exists nothing is done.

Returns a [:Future<Directory>:] that completes with this
directory once it has been created. If the directory cannot be
created the future completes with an exception.

children.name: createSync
children.comment:
Synchronously creates the directory with this name.

If [recursive] is false, only the last directory in the path is
created. If [recursive] is true, all non-existing path components
are created. If the directory already exists nothing is done.

If the directory cannot be created an exception is thrown.

children.name: createTemp
children.comment:
Creates a temporary directory with a name based on the current
path.  This name and path is used as a template, and additional
characters are appended to it by the call to make a unique
directory name.  If the path is the empty string, a default
system temp directory and name are used for the template.

Returns a [:Future<Directory>:] that completes with the newly
created temporary directory.

children.name: createTempSync
children.comment:
Synchronously creates a temporary directory with a name based on the
current path. This name and path is used as a template, and additional
characters are appended to it by the call to make a unique directory name.
If the path is the empty string, a default system temp directory and name
are used for the template. Returns the newly created temporary directory.

children.name: delete
children.comment:
Deletes the directory with this name.

If [recursive] is false, the directory must be empty.

If [recursive] is true, this directory and all sub-directories
and files in the directories are deleted.

Returns a [:Future<Directory>:] that completes with this
directory when the deletion is done. If the directory cannot be
deleted, the future completes with an exception.

children.name: deleteSync
children.comment:
Synchronously deletes the directory with this name.

If [recursive] is false, the directory must be empty.

If [recursive] is true, this directory and all sub-directories
and files in the directories are deleted.

Throws an exception if the directory cannot be deleted.

children.name: rename
children.comment:
Rename this directory. Returns a [:Future<Directory>:] that completes
with a [Directory] instance for the renamed directory.

If newPath identifies an existing directory, that directory is
replaced. If newPath identifies an existing file the operation
fails and the future completes with an exception.

children.name: renameSync
children.comment:
Synchronously rename this directory. Returns a [Directory]
instance for the renamed directory.

If newPath identifies an existing directory, that directory is
replaced. If newPath identifies an existing file the operation
fails and an exception is thrown.

children.name: list
children.comment:
List the sub-directories and files of this
[Directory]. Optionally recurse into sub-directories. Returns a
[DirectoryLister] object representing the active listing
operation. Handlers for files and directories should be
registered on this DirectoryLister object.

children.name: listSync
children.comment:
List the sub-directories and files of this
[Directory]. Optionally recurse into sub-directories. Returns a
List containing Directory and File objects.

children.name: toString
children.comment: Returns a human readable string for this Directory instance.

children.name: Directory
children.comment:
Creates a directory object. The path is either an absolute path,
or it is a relative path which is interpreted relative to the directory
in which the Dart VM was started.

children.name: Directory.fromPath
children.comment:
Creates a directory object from a Path object. The path is either
an absolute path, or it is a relative path which is interpreted
relative to the directory in which the Dart VM was started.

children.name: Directory.current
children.comment:
Creates a directory object pointing to the current working
directory.
[Directory] objects are used for working with directories.

children.name: OSError
toString
children.comment: Converts an OSError object to a string representation.

children.name: OSError
children.comment: Creates an OSError object from a message and an errorCode.

An [OSError] object holds information about an error from the
operating system.

children.name: _BufferList
add
children.comment:
Adds a new buffer to the list possibly with an offset of the
first byte of interest. The offset can only be specified if the
buffer list is empty.

children.name: peek
children.comment: Peek at the next available byte.

children.name: next
children.comment: Returns the next available byte removing it from the buffers.

children.name: readBytes
children.comment:
Read [count] bytes from the buffer list. If the number of bytes
requested is not available null will be returned.

children.name: removeBytes
children.comment:
Remove a number of bytes from the buffer list. Currently the
number of bytes to remove must be confined to the first buffer.

children.name: clear
children.comment: Clears the content of the buffer list.

children.name: first
children.comment:
Returns the first buffer from the list. This returns the whole
buffer and does not remove the buffer from the list. Use
[index] to determine the index of the first byte in the buffer.

children.name: index
children.comment:
Returns the current index of the next byte. This will always be
an index into the first buffer as when the index is advanced past
the end of a buffer it is removed from the list.

children.name: length
children.comment: Returns the total number of bytes remaining in the buffers.

children.name: isEmpty
children.comment:
Returns whether the buffer list is empty that is has no bytes
available.

Utility class that holds a number of byte buffers and can deliver
the bytes either one by one or in chunks.

children.name: _encode
children.comment: Base64 transfer encoding for MIME (RFC 2045)

children.name: _decode
children.comment: Base64 transfer decoding for MIME (RFC 2045).

comment:
The IO library is used for Dart server applications,
which run on a stand-alone Dart VM from the command line.
*This library does not work in browser based applications.*

This library allows you to work with files, directories,
sockets, processes, HTTP servers and clients, and more.
